{{Quote|These smaller coffins must belong to Queen Amanoa and King Ommin, the dark-side rulers of Onderon! They are of no interest to me. That large one! That must be&hellip;''"<br />"''The Tomb of Freedon Nadd&mdash;''my tomb!''|Exar Kun and Freedon Nadd's spirit|audio=TombOfFreedonNadd-DLOTS.flac|<ref name="DLOTSA" />}}
The '''Tomb of Freedon Nadd''' was a mausoleum that served as the final resting place for the physical remains of [[King/Legends|King]] [[Ommin/Legends|Ommin]] and [[Queen/Legends|Queen]] [[Amanoa]] of [[Onderon/Legends|Onderon]], as well as their [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] ancestor, the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord]] [[Freedon Nadd]]. The original tomb, which consisted of nothing more than [[Freedon Nadd's sarcophagus|Nadd's sarcophagus]] within a hollowed section beneath the [[Iziz Royal Palace|royal palace]] of [[Iziz/Legends|Iziz]], was cleansed of its [[Vergence/Legends|potency]] with the [[Battle of Iziz|end]] of the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Onderon/Legends|Onderon's]] [[Beast Wars]]. After the [[Second Battle of Onderon|final defeat]] of [[Naddist|Freedon Nadd's worshippers]] in [[3998 BBY]], [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Arca Jeth]] ordered the construction of a new tomb on the nearby jungle [[Moon/Legends|moon]] [[Dxun/Legends|Dxun]] to contain Nadd's remains and their residual [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side energies]]. Entombed alongside the Dark Lord were Queen Amanoa and King Ommin, with whom died the last vestiges of Nadd's [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] dynasty.

Freedon Nadd's tomb was visited a [[3997 BBY|year later]] by the [[Dark Jedi/Legends|Dark Jedi]] [[Exar Kun/Legends|Exar Kun]], who penetrated its [[Beskar/Legends|nearly-indestructible]] exterior in search of forbidden secrets. The tomb remained unvisited for nearly the next [[3951 BBY|forty years]], when Sith forces loyal to the Dark Lord [[Darth Nihilus]] were defeated by companions of [[Meetra Surik]]. [[990 BBY|Three millennia later]], Nadd's tomb was found and explored by the [[Sith'ari/Legends|Sith'ari]] [[Darth Bane/Legends|Darth Bane]], wherein he discovered [[Freedon Nadd's holocron|Nadd's holocron]], and the [[orbalisk]] Force-parasites.

==Structure==
===Onderon tomb===
{{Quote|These catacombs under the city extend for miles. Many people have wandered down here and been lost forever.[&hellip;]They say the tomb of the Dark Jedi, Freedon Nadd, is hidden down here, but that's just a myth.|Princess Galia|<ref name="BWOO2" />}}
[[File:FreedonNaddTempleExterior.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The Tomb of Freedon Nadd on Dxun.]]
The original tomb of the ancient [[Padawan/Legends|Jedi apprentice]]-turned-[[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]] [[Freedon Nadd]] consisted of nothing more than a hidden cave beneath the [[Iziz Royal Palace|royal palace]] of [[Iziz/Legends|Iziz]], the [[Capital/Legends|capital]] [[City/Legends|city]] of the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Onderon/Legends|Onderon]].<ref name="TOTJA" /> A secret, winding, tunnel known only to Iziz's [[Queen/Legends|Queen]] [[Amanoa]] was the single means by which the tomb was reached.<ref name="BWOO2" /> Damp,<ref name="TOTJA" /> dark,<ref name="BWOO2" /> and cold, the path led to a large, heavy stone slab that barred further entry, behind which was a cave<ref name="TOTJA" /> with the capacity to support only a handful of [[Sentience/Legends|beings]] at any given time. Because the enormous [[Freedon Nadd's sarcophagus|sarcophagus of Freedon Nadd]]<ref name="BWOO2" /> was an [[Sith artifact/Legends|object]] of potent [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side power]] itself, the tomb in which it was kept became a [[Vergence/Legends|reservoir]] of malevolent [[The Force/Legends|Force energy]], which in turn suffused Iziz, then the planet, and eventually the entirety of the [[Japrael system/Legends|Onderon system]] with the power of [[Sith sorcery/Legends|Sith magic]]. The tomb of Freedon Nadd beneath the Iziz royal palace therefore served as the seat of Queen Amanoa's power, whereto she withdrew in times of great peril to [[Invoke spirits|summon]] the [[Force ghost/Legends|spirit]] and power of Freedon Nadd himself. Despite the secrecy that shrouded its location, however, rumors of the existence of Nadd's tomb were prevalent among the citizens of Onderon.<ref name="TOTJA" />

===Dxun tomb===
{{Quote|There. Is that the place you spoke of?''"<br />"''Yes! On the far side of that moon&hellip;that's where that accursed Jedi Master hid the tomb of Freedon Nadd.|Exar Kun, and Nebo|audio=TombOfFreedonNaddDxunHistory-DLOTS.flac|<ref name="DLOTSA" />}}
Following the [[Second Battle of Onderon|end]] of the [[Freedon Nadd Uprising|Naddist insurrection]] in [[3998 BBY]], the Dark Lord's tomb was relocated to an obsidian, tiered,<ref name="FNU2" /> trapezoidal edifice fortress of nigh-impenetrable, mirror-surfaced<ref name="DLOTS2" /> [[Beskar/Legends|Mandalorian iron]],<ref name="DLOTSA" /> on the nearby moon of [[Dxun/Legends|Dxun]]. A single road led to a circular bastion replete with spiked and cannon-equipped emplacements to repel treasure-seekers and plunderers alike, all surrounded by a deep trench. The avenue branched off in either direction once passed the fortification's threshold, but the primary thoroughfare continued just past enormous braziers with fires blazing at the foot of the tomb, and ended at a long staircase situated between ramparts on either side that led to the temple's entrance.<ref name="FNU2" /> At the summit of the stairs was a long avenue lined with four statues, two on either side, of sword-armed beings whose weapons were extended outward but pointed down.<ref name="KotOR II game" /> A pair of monoliths the height of the tomb's main structure protruded upward on both sides of the building, with another set of smaller plinths flanking the entrance.<ref name="DLOTS2" /> The dark side power that emanated from the tomb warped the structure of the building over time;<ref name="RoT" /> merely [[3997 BBY|two years]] after its construction, iron outcroppings had jutted upward near the entrance,<ref name="DLOTS2" /> and subsequent centuries of malevolent infusion dimpled the walls of the tomb so that it eventually became more pyramidal, yet asymmetrical, in appearance. Even the monoliths had been drawn in close to the building, their prominent and upright erection reduced to curved parallels of the temple's shape.<ref name="KotOR II game" />

The interior of Freedon Nadd's tomb opened to a small, low-ceiling antechamber, with passages that branched off in three separate directions. In the main chamber, amongst a menagerie of Sith treasure and artifacts,<ref name="DLOTS2" /> were the sarcophagi of Onderon's dark side elite: King Ommin and Queen Amanoa, and their [[Sith Master/Legends|Sith Master]], Freedon Nadd.<ref name="DLOTSA" /> The path to the left of the antechamber led down a hall lined with various chambers, and eventually split into several winding routes. At the tunnel's end was the heart of the tomb, where a small chamber was barred by a tight-fitting, meter-wide slab of [[Black|ebony]] [[Stone/Legends|stone]]. Behind the black door was a circular room about five meters in height and diameter, with a stone pedestal in the exact center, on top of which sat the [[Freedon Nadd's holocron|holocron of Freedon Nadd]]. The [[Sith holocron/Legends|device]] was protected by an entire colony of [[orbalisk]] [[Parasite/Legends|parasites]] that covered the expanse of the chamber.<ref name="RoT" /> Decades after the tomb's consecration, Freedon Nadd's husk was moved to an adjacent room where a shrine had been dedicated to the performance of rituals in his name. A single torch-bearing statue was situated on either side of a raised altar that also housed the new sarcophagus. Three additional torches were set directly in front, behind which was a long rectangular pool of [[Water/Legends|water]]. Atop the mausoleum was a massive platformed statue of Freedon Nadd, and within were the Dark Lord's remains, and his [[Freedon Nadd's short lightsaber|personal lightsaber]].<ref name="KotOR II game" />

==History==
===Beast Wars===
{{Quote|Those cursed Jedi will never find me here, heheheh&hellip;buried within the depths of the palace, with the Tomb of Freedon Nadd.|Amanoa|audio=TombOfFreedonNaddStructure-TOTJ.flac|<ref name="TOTJA" />}}
[[File:NaddsRemains-TOTJKOTOR2.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Freedon Nadd's remains were kept in the bowels of the Iziz royal palace.]]
In [[4000 BBY/Legends|4000 BBY]], when the forces of Iziz went to war against the combined might of the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] and [[Modon Kira]]'s [[Beast Riders]], Amanoa quietly sneaked away under her palace to Nadd's tomb, and drew fully on the power of the dark side focused in his remains. Chanting his name, Amanoa [[Sith sorcery/Legends|invoked]] Nadd's spirit and used its power to cause panic and terror amongst the armies of Beast Riders. However, when confronted by the [[Force Light|light]] of [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Arca Jeth]], the shadow of Nadd's [[Force ghost/Legends|spirit]] was driven from the tomb. Amanoa died, the shadow having been driven from her as well.<ref name="TOTJA" />

To purge the dark side from Onderon permanently, Jeth planned to relocate the sarcophagus along with Amanoa's coffin to Onderon's nearby moon, Dxun. He surmised that the moon's natural fauna would be more than sufficient in deterring any would-be grave robbers. But before the sarcophagi could be moved, they were stolen by the [[Dark Jedi/Legends|Dark Jedi]] [[Warb Null]] and his army of Naddists, who surprised the Jedi from below with a massive tunnel-boring war machine and confiscated the coffins, retreating with them into the tunnels underground. Master Jeth and his [[Padawan/Legends|Jedi apprentice]] [[Ulic Qel-Droma/Legends|Ulic Qel-Droma]], led by Queen Galia, followed the [[Naddist]]s underground where they discovered Warb Null and King Ommin, who was alive and, much to their horror, in league with Freedon Nadd's spirit. Though Ommin was able to subdue and capture Jeth with his [[Force lightning/Legends|Force lightning]], the Jedi Master was eventually rescued by a team of [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knights]]. Ommin was killed, and Nadd's spirit was finally removed from Onderon. Jeth took the sarcophagi of King Ommin, Queen Amanoa, and Freedon Nadd, and finally moved them to Dxun. Building an actual mausoleum of Mandalorian iron, Jeth sealed the tomb and placed it in a remote area of Dxun, to be hopefully left undisturbed.<ref name="FNU2" />

===Post-Naddist Uprising===
{{Quote|To prevent Freedon Nadd from ever exercising his power from beyond the grave, I have transferred his sarcophagus to a great tomb on another world. The tomb is guarded by many beasts. May no one dare to find it.|Arca Jeth|<ref name="EGTTF" />}}
[[File:KunAtTheTomb-TOTJDarkLords2.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Freedon Nadd's tomb is visited by Exar Kun.]]
Beings who were themselves steeped in the dark side felt compelled to seek out the source of Dxun's powerful miasma that was the tomb of Freedon Nadd.<ref name="RoT" /> In [[3997 BBY]], it was discovered by the Jedi [[Exar Kun/Legends|Exar Kun]] who managed to break in after finally penetrating the wall with his lightsaber. Upon entering he was confronted by Freedon Nadd's [[Force ghost/Legends|ghost]], who directed him to the scrolls hidden under his bones. The scrolls pointed Kun to [[Korriban/Legends|Korriban]], where he would be reunited with Nadd, [[Sith apprentice/Legends|apprenticed]] to him and acquire tremendous Sith powers. After the second death of Freedon Nadd, his spirit was banished to [[Chaos/Legends|Chaos]], and the tomb would remain undisturbed for little more than thirty years.<ref name="TOTJA" /><ref name="DLOTS2" />

===Second Battle of Onderon===
{{Quote|Can't you feel the power of this place? It echoes through you like a second voice. Accept it&hellip; embrace it.|A [[Unidentified Sith Master (Dxun)|Sith Master]] attempts to turn a member of Meetra Surik's crew to the dark side|<ref name="KotOR II game" />}}
In [[3951 BBY]], the tomb was critical to the outcome of the [[Battle of Onderon (Onderon Civil War)|Second Battle of Onderon]]. Sith forces under the Sith Lord [[Darth Nihilus]] and a [[Unidentified Sith Master (Dxun)|Sith Master]] used Freedon Nadd's tomb as a base to support the Onderonian [[General/Legends|General]] [[Vaklu]] and his [[Onderon separatists|forces]], who wished to overthrow Queen [[Talia (Onderon)|Talia]]. Transmissions from the Sith were tracked by the [[Mandalorians (Clan Ordo)|Mandalorians]] under the Mandalorian [[Kelborn]]. The current Mandalorian leader, [[Canderous Ordo|Mandalore the Preserver]], was journeying with the Jedi Knight [[Meetra Surik]], known as the Jedi Exile in a quest to reunite the scattered Mandalorian clans. When Surik and her companions met with Kelborn, a companion of Surik's, Jedi Master [[Kreia]], recognized that the Sith were on Dxun, and counseled action against the Sith. Before Surik headed to Onderon to assist the [[Onderon Royalist|Royalists]] loyal to Queen Talia, she charged three of her companions with stopping these Sith. Surik's companions successfully prevented the [[Sith Master/Legends|Sith Masters]] in the tomb from performing a dark side ritual.<ref name="KotOR II game" />

About [[990 BBY|three thousand years later]], the Sith Lord Darth Bane traveled to Freedon Nadd's tomb in search of potential secrets for creating [[Holocron/Legends|holocrons]]. When he entered the tomb, Bane was displeased to learn that someone had been there before him, though he did not know how long ago. He pressed on despite his disillusioned suspicion that his trip had been for nothing, until he happened upon an undisturbed chamber, sealed with thick slab of Mandalorian iron. At first Bane was not able to enter the room, but then he used the dark side to throw the door across the room. Then, he saw that the room held its own holocron. Bane soon learned that the holocron was not the only thing housed in that room. The secret chamber was infested with [[orbalisk]], tiny crustacean-like creatures that feed on the power of the dark side. When Bane tried to remove the holocron, two of the orbalisks attached themselves to him, one to his chest and the other on his back. Lord Bane remained in the tomb for four days while he delved into its crystal lattices, after which he left the tomb and Dxun with the holocron as well.<ref name="RoT">''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]''</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:Dxun_Temple_concept_art.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Concept art of Freedon Nadd's Tomb.]]
The Dxun tomb of Freedon Nadd was first introduced in the [[Star Wars: Tales of the Jedi – The Freedon Nadd Uprising|''The Freedon Nadd Uprising'']] story arc of the [[Star Wars: Tales of the Jedi (comic series)|''Tales of the Jedi'']] series of [[Star Wars comic books|comic books]], published by [[Dark Horse Comics]] in [[1994]]. The burial site was later featured in the [[2004]] [[Star Wars video games|video game]] ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]'', developed by [[Obsidian Entertainment]]. Nadd's tomb serves as a key plot element within the game's storyline.<ref name="KotOR II game" /> Nadd's tomb was mentioned in Freedon Nadd's entry in ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.

In ''Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords'', if the leader of the expedition to the tomb has training in the ways of the Force, he or she has a chance to acquire new powers in the tomb, drawing upon a pair of dark side energy nexuses that could be found in the tomb. The first nexus offers the power of [[Force Slow|Slow]], while the second can grant the power of [[Force Slow|Affliction]], provided neither power has yet been chosen by that character during level-up. Alternately, if the character chooses to control their emotions and successfully resists, a temporary bonus to strength and constitution stats can be earned. Surik's companion in charge of the mission to Freedon Nadd's tomb is recognized as a Force-sensitive by the Sith Master and his fellow Masters. The Sith Master offered the leader a chance to embrace the dark side and the power that the Sith were harnessing to control the beasts on Onderon and Dxun.<ref name="KotOR II game" />

